metadata.name: CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE #240
metadata.description:
1 of 5 in CENTURY-XXX, Series 2
Edition of 1000

Tribute to Herbert W. Franke
‚ÄúIn Honor of the Dinosaur of Computer Art‚Äù 

Herbert W. Franke, a pioneer of computer art, passed away on July 16, 2022 at the age of 95. CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE is an homage to Franke‚Äôs MONDRIAN software developed for the Texas Instruments TI 99/4 home computer in 1979, and it‚Äôs a fundraiser to digitize his archive:

‚ÄúOur goal is to raise 20,000 Euro so that ZKM Karlsruhe can digitize Herbert W. Franke‚Äôs 1,800 manuscripts and make them publicly available. If we raise more money, it will be donated to the R√ºtgers Foundation which supports children and young adults in Africa so that they can get access to and work with technology.‚Äù 

Each frame, a single ‚Äúpixel‚Äù is added to the CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE image. When the software first loads, 100,000 frames are run in the background to start things off. Keep it running for hours or days to see it transform entirely ‚Äî it‚Äôs an ‚Äúinfinite animation.‚Äù

metadata.name: soul materium #20
metadata.description:
Today I present to you the "material of the soul".
Artwork generates three-dimensional waves, creating an incredible pattern of matter.

The soul is as important a part of you as the body. Only your soul decides if you like the artwork. She always knows you better than anyone, and no matter how much you deny her desires, she will always be right. She can hurt, love, hope .. Or is it all the same?

metadata.name: Rite of Passage #179
metadata.description:
In life, we all take different paths, different rites of passage, and while the end is all that's ever true, we will still all view it and experience it in very different ways, like that masterpiece hanging on the wall at the end of our gallery visit. 
  

There are always things that we will never have the power to change, but at the same time, we determine the route, we influence the journey, we can choose the person we want to be. We'll look back on memories, we'll have regrets, and we'll think about what could have been - but unlike this artwork, in the end we won't be able to change the final output by simply pressing a number - so live well and be happy my friends. 

---------------------

Generative artwork by Sykcolo / @sykcoloart

Primary sale proceeds:
50% to Processing Foundation
50% to Savepakistan

Royalties:
50% to the original minter
50% to artist (me)

Press '2' to '4' to see what could have been + increase pixel density. 
Press 's' to save

150 hand-picked colour pallets (thanks to @SteveMakerspace for colour selection method)
2 Frame types
4 Art types

metadata.name: Sweeping #52
metadata.description:
Sweeping is a piece in which I explore the uses of noise fields. Using them in the most cliche way possible, but trying to make something unique out of that.

What started out as an innocent weekend project grew out to be quite the piece, which is why I am publishing it here.



Sweeping uses the GPU of your machine for its shading, which means it won't run particularly well on mobile devices. My recommended way of viewing this piece is on a PC with a dedicated GPU.

---

- Double Click to open a User Interface
- In the UI, you can toggle the paper texture and export

---

Made with p5js + webgl by Wouter Missler, 2022.

metadata.name: Boggle #247
metadata.description:
Boggle was inspired by a series of OP Art paintings done by Victor Vasarely, called Vonal-F√®ny. (c. 1975). Vasarely died in 1997 in the early days of computer art. I'm sure he would have embraced this medium. This is the forth in a series of Vasarely inspired Generative Art pieces I am offering.

I became interested in Victor Vasarely's graphic artworks while I was in art school. As I struggled to learn computer graphics I wondered how do I write a program to produce imagery with a similar aesthetic? I call the process of creating algorithms inspired by other artists: "Art"ificial Intelligence.

Brain Boggle is a multiple square arrangement of the original work. I was able to decipher Vasarely's painting into an algorithm and thereby generalize it. I can vary the number of points in each half of the square and I can rotate the square in 90 degree increments. I like putting the one of four rotational variations of the piece together in a 2x2 array. All the pointed shapes are one random color. To me the interactions between each section is more interesting than 4 instances at the same rotation angle. 

The overall background is random, either a solid color or one of 4 types of linear gradients.

Dr. Bill Generative Art OG @ drbillkolomyjec.com

metadata.description:

Please note that it takes about 5-10 seconds for the artwork to start loading. And it‚Äôs best viewed on a screen bigger than a mobile phone, while listening to this track called ‚ÄòWish You Were Here' by Pink Floyd: 
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hjpF8ukSrvk

Artwork loads at 1000px by 1000px resolution by default. Press ‚Äò2‚Äô,‚Äô4‚Äô or ‚Äò8‚Äô to load as 2000px by 2000px, 4000px by 4000px or 8000px by 8000px respectively.
Press 's' at any time to download the rendered resolution.

metadata.name: Harmony in chaos #23
metadata.description:
The human spirit is an enigmatic one-of-a-kind. It has always been a conundrum for people who want to understand the depth of it, but no one has ever made it through. Once generated, the spirit is like a blank canvas; everyone has a slightly different spirit hue. As time goes, our spirits grow more influenced by our daily activities, emotions, and feelings... We intend to view the front of the surface of it, as we do with everything, but there are numerous scratches, scars, and traces beneath the surface.

metadata.name: Let's Celebrate #14
metadata.description:
All peoples have established anniversaries to celebrate their victories, disorders, or misfortunes.
Having said that, people are social beings, and you cannot celebrate whatever it may be alone. So join those who are celebrating 
their success because they will join you in celebrating yours when the time comes. Then, as you praise and celebrate your life, 
there will be more life to enjoy. For all of the humans out there, remember that celebrations don't have to revolve around grandiose 
things. It's okay to celebrate a simple life. However, for all of us pursuing our passions, remember that although celebrating 
achievement is significant, learning from failure is much more crucial. while you cherish the milestones as you prepare for the road 
ahead.

Fxhash turns one, Happy birthday !
